Name: OCTAMETHYLCYCLOTETRASILOXANE
Description: Octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane is a cyclosiloxane that is the octamethyl derivative of cyclotetrasiloxane. It is an organosilicon compound and a cyclosiloxane. It derives from a hydride of a cyclotetrasiloxane.

animal_concentrations.Value: Analysis of seal blubber from grey seals (Halichoerus grypus) found in Sweden in 2008 detected octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane levels of <3 ng/g wet weight(1).

fish_seafood_concentrations.References: (1) Kierkegaard A et al; Environ Sci Technol 45: 5936-42 (2011) (2) Kierkegaard A et al; Chemosphere 93: 774-78 (2013) (3) ECHA; Search for Chemicals. Octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane (CAS 556-67-2) Registered Substances Dossier. European Chemical Agency. Available from, as of Aug 17, 2015: https://echa.europa.eu/
fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Flounder (Pleuronectes flesus) collected from six sites in the lower Humber estuary in England in 2009 contained octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of <1.6-10.4 ng/g wet weight(1). Herring (Clupea harengus) collected off the Swedish coast in 2007 contained octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of 1-37 ng/g lipid wet(2). Fish samples collected from Lake Erie in 2009 (common shiner, yellow perch, emerald shiner, trout perch, white perch, freshwater drum, walleye) contained mean octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations 7.9-13 ng/g wet weight(3). Fish collected from the Oslofjord Norway during a 2010 study (Atlantic herring, coalfish, common sole, Norway pout, European hake, starry skate, haddock, pollock, cod) contained mean octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of 2.3-26.8 ng/g wet weight and 98-504 ng/g lipid(3). A 2012 study that collected fish from the Toyko Bay Japan (Japanese sea bass, red barracuda, chub mackerel, dotted gizzard shad, Japanese anchovy, sardine, white croaker) detected mean octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of 8.4-24 ng/g wet weight(3).

sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: Sediment samples collected from six sites in the lower Humber estuary in England in 2009 contained octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of <0.9-16.6 ng/g dry weight(1). Twenty-five sediment samples collected from various sites of the Songhua River, China in 2009 contained octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of 0.98-33 mg/g with a mean concentration of 7.23 mg/g(2). Sediments collected from the Oslofjord Norway during a 2010 study contained mean octamethylcyclotetrasiloxane concentrations of 0.8-0.9 ng/g wet weight(3).
